& Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Spontaneous coronary artery dissection (SCAD) is a nonatherosclerotic cause of myocardial infarction in young and middle-aged women that has gained increasing awareness in recent years. Its diagnosis presents a challenge. Invasive coronary angiography is the primary imaging modality for diagnosing SCAD; however, it carries risk in these patients, who have an increased predisposition to complications. Advances in CT technology enable robust noninvasive evaluation of the coronary arteries at low radiation doses and have been increasingly utilized for the diagnosis or resolution of SCAD, in hemodynamically stable patients or when diagnosis of SCAD is uncertain at invasive angiography, particularly in proximal vessels. However, criteria for the diagnosis of SCAD with use of coronary CT angiography (CCTA) have not been currently established, and sensitivity and specificity for diagnosis have not yet been defined. The appearance of SCAD at CCTA can be subtle and can be missed, especially in distal small-caliber coronary arteries; hence utilization of other noninvasive imaging multimodalities may help solve this diagnostic challenge. Accurate and prompt diagnosis is vital, as management of SCAD differs significantly from that of traditional atherosclerotic acute coronary syndromes, with conservative management preferred for the majority of SCAD patients, and invasive treatment reserved for those with ongoing or recurrent ischemia, heart failure, or hemodynamic compromise. The goal of this review is twofold: <i>(a)</i> to discuss the potential role of CCTA in the diagnosis of SCAD, and <i>(b)</i> to discuss the role of multimodality imaging that may improve diagnostic yield, guide management, and enable subsequent surveillance.</div><div role="paragraph"><i>An invited commentary by <a href="https://pubs.rsna.org/doi/full/10.1148/rg.2021210202">Ordovas</a> is available online</i>.</div><div role="paragraph"><i>Online supplemental material is available for this article.</i></div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup>RSNA, 2021</div></section><section id="graphical-abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Visual Abstract</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="_i1" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210062/asset/images/large/rg.2021210062.va.jpeg" height="701" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210062&amp;id=_i1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figure></div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2021210062">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2021210062">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1" class="graphic" aria-label="Findings in a 45-year-old woman with no relevant past medical history who presented with a 3-day history of substernal chest pain. (A) Four-chamber late gadolinium-enhanced (LGE) image shows transmural LGE of the left ventricular (LV) apex (arrowhead). (B) Reevaluated multiplanar reformatted CCTA image shows smooth tapering of the LAD (white arrowhead) with smooth narrowing (black arrowhead) of the mid LAD, followed by significant narrowing and irregularity of distal LAD from intramural hematoma (IMH) (arrow). Adjacent fat stranding is seen. (C) CT findings correspond to subsequent cardiac catheterization findings of SCAD in the mid to distal LAD (circle)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210062/asset/images/large/rg.2021210062.fig1.jpeg" height="2372" width="2700" aria-labelledby="fig1" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1</span>. Findings in a 45-year-old woman with no relevant past medical history who presented with a 3-day history of substernal chest pain. <b>(A)</b> Four-chamber late gadolinium-enhanced (LGE) image shows transmural LGE of the left ventricular (LV) apex (arrowhead). <b>(B)</b> Reevaluated multiplanar reformatted CCTA image shows smooth tapering of the LAD (white arrowhead) with smooth narrowing (black arrowhead) of the mid LAD, followed by significant narrowing and irregularity of distal LAD from intramural hematoma (IMH) (arrow). Adjacent fat stranding is seen. <b>(C)</b> CT findings correspond to subsequent cardiac catheterization findings of SCAD in the mid to distal LAD (circle).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210062&amp;id=fig1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2" class="graphic" aria-label="Diagram illustrates the underlying pathogenesis of SCAD."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210062/asset/images/large/rg.2021210062.fig2.jpeg" height="1493" width="3000" aria-labelledby="fig2" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2</span>. Diagram illustrates the underlying pathogenesis of SCAD.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210062&amp;id=fig2">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3" class="graphic" aria-label="Diagram illustrates precipitating factors and clinical associations that predispose patients to SCAD. FMD = fibromuscular dysplasia."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210062/asset/images/large/rg.2021210062.fig3.jpeg" height="1979" width="2700" aria-labelledby="fig3" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3</span>. Diagram illustrates precipitating factors and clinical associations that predispose patients to SCAD. <i>FMD</i> = fibromuscular dysplasia.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210062&amp;id=fig3">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4" class="graphic" aria-label="Long QT and Brugada syndrome in a 24-year-old woman who had a pulseless electrical activity cardiac arrest after caesarean delivery. Troponin levels were significantly elevated, and ECG revealed Q waves with loss of voltage in lateral leads. (A) Cardiac catheterization image shows smooth stenosis of the left main artery (LM) (white arrow) extending into the proximal LAD (black arrow), resulting in 70% stenosis from IMH. (B–D) Curved planar reformatted CCTA image (B) and cross-sectional short-axis views of the LM (C, D) show a dissection flap in the LM (white arrow) and IMH in the proximal LAD (black arrow in D), resulting in 50%–70% smooth stenosis. Two years after the SCAD diagnosis, the patient presented with a right-sided headache. (E) Sagittal oblique maximum intensity projection (MIP) CT angiogram of the right internal carotid artery (ICA) shows tapering with irregular, multiple-channel, markedly small-caliber ICA (arrows), consistent with acute dissection. (F) Axial MIP image shows diminutive ICA (white arrowhead) from IMH and thrombosed false lumen. Note the normal-caliber left ICA (black arrowhead)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210062/asset/images/large/rg.2021210062.fig4.jpeg" height="2435" width="3800" aria-labelledby="fig4" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4</span>. Long QT and Brugada syndrome in a 24-year-old woman who had a pulseless electrical activity cardiac arrest after caesarean delivery. Troponin levels were significantly elevated, and ECG revealed Q waves with loss of voltage in lateral leads. <b>(A)</b> Cardiac catheterization image shows smooth stenosis of the left main artery (LM) (white arrow) extending into the proximal LAD (black arrow), resulting in 70% stenosis from IMH. <b>(B–D)</b> Curved planar reformatted CCTA image <b>(B)</b> and cross-sectional short-axis views of the LM <b>(C, D)</b> show a dissection flap in the LM (white arrow) and IMH in the proximal LAD (black arrow in <b>D</b>), resulting in 50%–70% smooth stenosis. Two years after the SCAD diagnosis, the patient presented with a right-sided headache. <b>(E)</b> Sagittal oblique maximum intensity projection (MIP) CT angiogram of the right internal carotid artery (ICA) shows tapering with irregular, multiple-channel, markedly small-caliber ICA (arrows), consistent with acute dissection. <b>(F)</b> Axial MIP image shows diminutive ICA (white arrowhead) from IMH and thrombosed false lumen. Note the normal-caliber left ICA (black arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210062&amp;id=fig4">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5" class="graphic" aria-label="Anatomic classifications of SCAD correlated with CCTA findings. Left panel: Diagram illustrates type 1 SCAD, which manifests as multiple lumens (arrows), contrast material staining, and complete occlusion distally at invasive coronary angiography. CCTA images (right) show a dissection flap (arrows) in the proximal RCA. Middle panel: Diagram illustrates type 2 SCAD: diffuse smooth stenosis of varying length (usually &gt;20 mm) and severity, such that diffuse narrowing (arrow) can be bordered by normal segments proximal and distal to IMH or extend to the distal tip of the artery. Corresponding CCTA image (right) shows smooth long-segment tapering of the LAD (arrows) that extends to the distal tip. Right panel: Diagram illustrates type 3 SCAD, characterized by focal stenosis (arrow in diagram) (usually &lt;20 mm) at invasive coronary angiography and as focal short-segment severe stenosis at CCTA (arrow, right image)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210062/asset/images/large/rg.2021210062.fig5.jpeg" height="1702" width="3400" aria-labelledby="fig5" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5</span>. Anatomic classifications of SCAD correlated with CCTA findings. Left panel: Diagram illustrates type 1 SCAD, which manifests as multiple lumens (arrows), contrast material staining, and complete occlusion distally at invasive coronary angiography. CCTA images (right) show a dissection flap (arrows) in the proximal RCA. Middle panel: Diagram illustrates type 2 SCAD: diffuse smooth stenosis of varying length (usually &gt;20 mm) and severity, such that diffuse narrowing (arrow) can be bordered by normal segments proximal and distal to IMH or extend to the distal tip of the artery. Corresponding CCTA image (right) shows smooth long-segment tapering of the LAD (arrows) that extends to the distal tip. Right panel: Diagram illustrates type 3 SCAD, characterized by focal stenosis (arrow in diagram) (usually &lt;20 mm) at invasive coronary angiography and as focal short-segment severe stenosis at CCTA (arrow, right image).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210062&amp;id=fig5">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6" class="graphic" aria-label="LAD aneurysm in a 50-year-old prediabetic woman with a history of migraine disorder who was admitted to the hospital with back pain followed by chest tightness and jaw ache. (A) Initial axial aortic CT angiogram shows an apparent linear filling defect in the LAD (arrow) that was reported as a possible dissection involving the aneurysmal LAD. (B) Subsequent dedicated axial coronary CT angiogram shows that there is no dissection flap (arrow). (C, D) Curved planar reformatted angiogram (C) shows fusiform aneurysm of the LAD, with a more focal aneurysm in the proximal and mid LAD containing a moderate amount of thrombus on the orthogonal cross-sectional view in the proximal LAD (arrow in D). There was no coronary artery dissection. The right coronary and left circumflex coronary arteries were diffusely ectatic and/or aneurysmal (not shown)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210062/asset/images/large/rg.2021210062.fig6.jpeg" height="2696" width="2700" aria-labelledby="fig6" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6</span>. LAD aneurysm in a 50-year-old prediabetic woman with a history of migraine disorder who was admitted to the hospital with back pain followed by chest tightness and jaw ache. <b>(A)</b> Initial axial aortic CT angiogram shows an apparent linear filling defect in the LAD (arrow) that was reported as a possible dissection involving the aneurysmal LAD. <b>(B)</b> Subsequent dedicated axial coronary CT angiogram shows that there is no dissection flap (arrow). <b>(C, D)</b> Curved planar reformatted angiogram <b>(C)</b> shows fusiform aneurysm of the LAD, with a more focal aneurysm in the proximal and mid LAD containing a moderate amount of thrombus on the orthogonal cross-sectional view in the proximal LAD (arrow in <b>D</b>). There was no coronary artery dissection. The right coronary and left circumflex coronary arteries were diffusely ectatic and/or aneurysmal (not shown).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210062&amp;id=fig6">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7" class="graphic" aria-label="RCA stenosis and FMD in a 40-year-old woman with a history of bipolar disorder and recent palpitations who presented with chest pain, elevated troponin levels, and unremarkable results of ECG performed at an outside institute. (A) Cardiac catheterization angiogram shows smooth tapering (black arrowhead) with tubular mid to distal 50% stenosis (black arrow) and distal 80% stenosis (white arrowhead), compatible with SCAD. A possible dissection flap in the proximal RCA is also seen as contrast medium hang-up (white arrow). The patient was managed with medication and readmitted with continued chest pain. Coronary CT angiography was ordered. (B) Curved planar reformatted RCA CT image shows smooth tapering (black arrowhead) with long smooth tubular, mid and distal RCA stenosis (black arrow), focal severe distal RCA stenosis (white arrowhead), and an intimal dissection flap in the proximal RCA (white arrow), corresponding to the invasive catheterization findings with no new SCAD findings. (C) Cross-sectional short-axis coronary CT angiogram shows focal severe distal RCA stenosis with surrounding IMH (arrowhead). (D) Head and neck CT angiogram obtained a month later in the workup for possible FMD shows beading of the bilateral cervical internal carotid arteries (arrowheads), consistent with FMD."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210062/asset/images/large/rg.2021210062.fig7.jpeg" height="3025" width="2600" aria-labelledby="fig7" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7</span>. RCA stenosis and FMD in a 40-year-old woman with a history of bipolar disorder and recent palpitations who presented with chest pain, elevated troponin levels, and unremarkable results of ECG performed at an outside institute. <b>(A)</b> Cardiac catheterization angiogram shows smooth tapering (black arrowhead) with tubular mid to distal 50% stenosis (black arrow) and distal 80% stenosis (white arrowhead), compatible with SCAD. A possible dissection flap in the proximal RCA is also seen as contrast medium hang-up (white arrow). The patient was managed with medication and readmitted with continued chest pain. Coronary CT angiography was ordered. <b>(B)</b> Curved planar reformatted RCA CT image shows smooth tapering (black arrowhead) with long smooth tubular, mid and distal RCA stenosis (black arrow), focal severe distal RCA stenosis (white arrowhead), and an intimal dissection flap in the proximal RCA (white arrow), corresponding to the invasive catheterization findings with no new SCAD findings. <b>(C)</b> Cross-sectional short-axis coronary CT angiogram shows focal severe distal RCA stenosis with surrounding IMH (arrowhead). <b>(D)</b> Head and neck CT angiogram obtained a month later in the workup for possible FMD shows beading of the bilateral cervical internal carotid arteries (arrowheads), consistent with FMD.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210062&amp;id=fig7">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8" class="graphic" aria-label="Findings in a 34-year-old man with a history of diabetes mellitus who presented with acute chest pain. Aortic CT did not depict acute aortic dissection or acute IMH. (A, B) Cardiac catheterization image (A) shows long, 90%-smooth proximal stenosis of the LAD (circle) and ostial first diagonal branch, secondary to underlying acute IMH (arrows in B), as seen on the intravascular US image (B). (C) Retrospective evaluation of the coronary arteries on the dedicated aortic CT image shows a severe abrupt short-segment stenosis (arrow) of the proximal LAD on the curved planar reformat. It is difficult to differentiate this from noncalcified plaque at CT, given the lower spatial resolution."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210062/asset/images/large/rg.2021210062.fig8.jpeg" height="1239" width="3800" aria-labelledby="fig8" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8</span>. Findings in a 34-year-old man with a history of diabetes mellitus who presented with acute chest pain. Aortic CT did not depict acute aortic dissection or acute IMH. <b>(A, B)</b> Cardiac catheterization image <b>(A)</b> shows long, 90%-smooth proximal stenosis of the LAD (circle) and ostial first diagonal branch, secondary to underlying acute IMH (arrows in <b>B</b>), as seen on the intravascular US image <b>(B)</b>. <b>(C)</b> Retrospective evaluation of the coronary arteries on the dedicated aortic CT image shows a severe abrupt short-segment stenosis (arrow) of the proximal LAD on the curved planar reformat. It is difficult to differentiate this from noncalcified plaque at CT, given the lower spatial resolution.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210062&amp;id=fig8">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9" class="graphic" aria-label="Findings in a 31-year-old woman with a history of Gilbert syndrome who presented with chest tightness and troponin leakage with akinesis of the apex, distal septum (SEP), and distal inferior (INF) wall at echocardiography, consistent with LAD infarct–non-STEMI. Aortic CT performed a week earlier showed possible fibroelastoma of the aortic valve. Coronary CT angiography was performed owing to concern for SCAD versus embolus. (A) Curved reformatted CCTA image of the LAD shows short-segment distal LAD severe stenosis (arrows), wall irregularity, decreased opacification, and adjacent fat stranding, consistent with type 3 SCAD.(B) Rubidium 82 (82Rb) PET myocardial perfusion scans show a large, severe, partially reversible defect in the apical segments consistent with ischemia and infarction in the territory typical of the distal LAD. Subsequent cardiac catheterization angiogram findings confirmed distal LAD SCAD with subtotal occlusion. The patient was managed with medication. ANT = anterior, HLA = horizontal long axis, LAT = lateral, SA = short axis, TOF = time of flight, VLA = vertical long axis."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210062/asset/images/large/rg.2021210062.fig9.jpeg" height="1661" width="3800" aria-labelledby="fig9" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9</span>. Findings in a 31-year-old woman with a history of Gilbert syndrome who presented with chest tightness and troponin leakage with akinesis of the apex, distal septum <i>(SEP),</i> and distal inferior <i>(INF)</i> wall at echocardiography, consistent with LAD infarct–non-STEMI. Aortic CT performed a week earlier showed possible fibroelastoma of the aortic valve. Coronary CT angiography was performed owing to concern for SCAD versus embolus. <b>(A)</b> Curved reformatted CCTA image of the LAD shows short-segment distal LAD severe stenosis (arrows), wall irregularity, decreased opacification, and adjacent fat stranding, consistent with type 3 SCAD. <b>(B)</b> Rubidium 82 (<sup>82</sup>Rb) PET myocardial perfusion scans show a large, severe, partially reversible defect in the apical segments consistent with ischemia and infarction in the territory typical of the distal LAD. Subsequent cardiac catheterization angiogram findings confirmed distal LAD SCAD with subtotal occlusion. The patient was managed with medication. <i>ANT</i> = anterior, <i>HLA</i> = horizontal long axis, <i>LAT</i> = lateral, <i>SA</i> = short axis, <i>TOF</i> = time of flight, <i>VLA</i> = vertical long axis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210062&amp;id=fig9">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10" class="graphic" aria-label="Findings in a 34-year-old woman after thyroidectomy and radioactive iodine treatment who presented with atypical chest pain radiating to both arms and the neck. Results of initial dual rule-out aortic and pulmonary embolism CT were negative. (A, B) Curved planar reformatted CCTA (A) and short-axis view (B) images of the RCA show smooth, long-segment mild stenosis of the proximal and mid RCA from acute IMH (arrowheads). (C) Coronal maximal intensity projection head CT angiogram shows a saccular aneurysm (arrow) of the supraclinoid segment of right internal carotid artery."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210062/asset/images/large/rg.2021210062.fig10.jpeg" height="2283" width="2700" aria-labelledby="fig10" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10</span>. Findings in a 34-year-old woman after thyroidectomy and radioactive iodine treatment who presented with atypical chest pain radiating to both arms and the neck. Results of initial dual rule-out aortic and pulmonary embolism CT were negative. <b>(A, B)</b> Curved planar reformatted CCTA <b>(A)</b> and short-axis view <b>(B)</b> images of the RCA show smooth, long-segment mild stenosis of the proximal and mid RCA from acute IMH (arrowheads). <b>(C)</b> Coronal maximal intensity projection head CT angiogram shows a saccular aneurysm (arrow) of the supraclinoid segment of right internal carotid artery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210062&amp;id=fig10">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11" class="graphic" aria-label="Dissection seen at cardiac MRI in a 33-year-old woman who presented with sudden-onset upper back pain and arm numbness when walking up a flight of stairs after skiing. The patient developed ventricular tachycardia and was diagnosed with anterior wall STEMI. Invasive coronary angiogram showed mid to distal LAD stenosis from SCAD, which was diagnosed at intravascular US. (A) Curved multiplanar reformatted MR angiogram shows stenosis (arrowhead) in the mid LAD. (B) Corresponding invasive coronary angiogram shows moderate tubular stenosis in the mid LAD (arrow). (C) Intravascular US image shows luminal stenosis with associated large IMH (arrow). (D) Late gadolinium-enhanced left ventricular outflow tract, long-axis MR image shows nearly transmural enhancement (arrowheads) and low signal intensity associated with microvascular obstruction. These findings are compatible with myocardial infarction in the mid and distal LAD territories."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210062/asset/images/large/rg.2021210062.fig11.jpeg" height="3157" width="2700" aria-labelledby="fig11" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11</span>. Dissection seen at cardiac MRI in a 33-year-old woman who presented with sudden-onset upper back pain and arm numbness when walking up a flight of stairs after skiing. The patient developed ventricular tachycardia and was diagnosed with anterior wall STEMI. Invasive coronary angiogram showed mid to distal LAD stenosis from SCAD, which was diagnosed at intravascular US. <b>(A)</b> Curved multiplanar reformatted MR angiogram shows stenosis (arrowhead) in the mid LAD. <b>(B)</b> Corresponding invasive coronary angiogram shows moderate tubular stenosis in the mid LAD (arrow). <b>(C)</b> Intravascular US image shows luminal stenosis with associated large IMH (arrow). <b>(D)</b> Late gadolinium-enhanced left ventricular outflow tract, long-axis MR image shows nearly transmural enhancement (arrowheads) and low signal intensity associated with microvascular obstruction. These findings are compatible with myocardial infarction in the mid and distal LAD territories.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210062&amp;id=fig11">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12" class="graphic" aria-label="Takotsubo cardiomyopathy secondary to vasospasm in a 71-year-old woman with fever, cough, chest pressure, and elevated high-sensitivity troponin levels, who underwent coronary catheterization, which showed no obstructive coronary artery disease. (A) Echocardiogram shows a dyskinetic apical left ventricle with apical ballooning during systole (arrows). (B, C) Horizontal long-axis SSFP (B) and gadolinium-enhanced horizontal long-axis (C) cardiac MR images show a dyskinetic apical left ventricle with apical ballooning during systole (arrows in B) and no evidence of late gadolinium enhancement (arrows in C). The findings were compatible with Takotsubo cardiomyopathy secondary to vasospasm. (Case courtesy of Juan Lopez-Mattei, MD, MD Anderson Cancer Center, Houston, Tex.)"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210062/asset/images/large/rg.2021210062.fig12.jpeg" height="1247" width="3800" aria-labelledby="fig12" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12</span>. Takotsubo cardiomyopathy secondary to vasospasm in a 71-year-old woman with fever, cough, chest pressure, and elevated high-sensitivity troponin levels, who underwent coronary catheterization, which showed no obstructive coronary artery disease. <b>(A)</b> Echocardiogram shows a dyskinetic apical left ventricle with apical ballooning during systole (arrows). <b>(B, C)</b> Horizontal long-axis SSFP <b>(B)</b> and gadolinium-enhanced horizontal long-axis <b>(C)</b> cardiac MR images show a dyskinetic apical left ventricle with apical ballooning during systole (arrows in <b>B</b>) and no evidence of late gadolinium enhancement (arrows in <b>C</b>). The findings were compatible with Takotsubo cardiomyopathy secondary to vasospasm. (Case courtesy of Juan Lopez-Mattei, MD, MD Anderson Cancer Center, Houston, Tex.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210062&amp;id=fig12">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13" class="graphic" aria-label="Elevated high-sensitivity troponin levels in a 42-year-old woman who presented to the emergency department with chest pain radiating to the left shoulder. Cardiac catheterization revealed normal coronary arteries. Cardiac MRI (not shown) depicted hypokinesis of the mid inferolateral wall on cine SSFP images. (A) Short-axis T2-weighted cardiac MR image shows high signal intensity (arrow) of the mid inferolateral wall. (B) Short-axis cardiac MR image shows corresponding transmural late gadolinium enhancement (arrow). The presence of vasogenic edema was suggestive of myocarditis. (C) Short-axis cardiac PET/CT image shows FDG avidity (fat loading or heparin) in the mid inferolateral wall (arrow), corresponding to the cardiac MRI findings."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210062/asset/images/large/rg.2021210062.fig13.jpeg" height="1247" width="3800" aria-labelledby="fig13" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13</span>. Elevated high-sensitivity troponin levels in a 42-year-old woman who presented to the emergency department with chest pain radiating to the left shoulder. Cardiac catheterization revealed normal coronary arteries. Cardiac MRI (not shown) depicted hypokinesis of the mid inferolateral wall on cine SSFP images. <b>(A)</b> Short-axis T2-weighted cardiac MR image shows high signal intensity (arrow) of the mid inferolateral wall. <b>(B)</b> Short-axis cardiac MR image shows corresponding transmural late gadolinium enhancement (arrow). The presence of vasogenic edema was suggestive of myocarditis. <b>(C)</b> Short-axis cardiac PET/CT image shows FDG avidity (fat loading or heparin) in the mid inferolateral wall (arrow), corresponding to the cardiac MRI findings.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210062&amp;id=fig13">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14" class="graphic" aria-label="Non-STEMI in a 43-year-old woman with a history of hypothyroidism who presented to an outside hospital with chest pain after prolonged upper respiratory viral illness. Her high-sensitivity troponin levels were elevated. Coronary catheterization revealed normal coronary arteries. (A, B) Subsequent SSFP left ventricular outflow tract (LVOT) long-axis cardiac MR images show apical septum akinesis (arrow) at end diastole (A) and end systole (B). (C) Long-axis LVOT late gadolinium enhancement (LGE) MR image shows near-transmural LGE of the apical septum and left ventricular apex (arrow) compatible with MINOCA. (D) Short-axis T2-weighted fat-saturated MR image shows no myocardial high signal intensity in the apex to suggest vasogenic edema or myocarditis."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210062/asset/images/large/rg.2021210062.fig14.jpeg" height="2698" width="2700" aria-labelledby="fig14" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14</span>. Non-STEMI in a 43-year-old woman with a history of hypothyroidism who presented to an outside hospital with chest pain after prolonged upper respiratory viral illness. Her high-sensitivity troponin levels were elevated. Coronary catheterization revealed normal coronary arteries. <b>(A, B)</b> Subsequent SSFP left ventricular outflow tract (LVOT) long-axis cardiac MR images show apical septum akinesis (arrow) at end diastole <b>(A)</b> and end systole <b>(B)</b>. <b>(C)</b> Long-axis LVOT late gadolinium enhancement (LGE) MR image shows near-transmural LGE of the apical septum and left ventricular apex (arrow) compatible with MINOCA. <b>(D)</b> Short-axis T2-weighted fat-saturated MR image shows no myocardial high signal intensity in the apex to suggest vasogenic edema or myocarditis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210062&amp;id=fig14">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15" class="graphic" aria-label="Findings in a patient with a known diagnosis of SCAD determined with invasive coronary angiography (not shown). Volume-rendered workup CT angiogram of the abdominal aorta shows beaded contour irregularity of the renal (white arrows) and external iliac (black arrows) arteries and mild ectasia of the right common iliac artery (arrowhead) compatible with multifocal FMD."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210062/asset/images/large/rg.2021210062.fig15.jpeg" height="1400" width="1400" aria-labelledby="fig15" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15</span>. Findings in a patient with a known diagnosis of SCAD determined with invasive coronary angiography (not shown). Volume-rendered workup CT angiogram of the abdominal aorta shows beaded contour irregularity of the renal (white arrows) and external iliac (black arrows) arteries and mild ectasia of the right common iliac artery (arrowhead) compatible with multifocal FMD.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210062&amp;id=fig15">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16" class="graphic" aria-label="SCAD in a 36-year-old, 3-months-postpartum woman who was diagnosed with STEMI at an outside institution and treated with drug-eluting stents to the mid and distal LAD and first obtuse marginal branch (OM1) for subtotal LAD occlusion, possible SCAD, and probable thrombotic OM1 occlusion. On continued chest pain following percutaneous coronary intervention, she was transferred to our institution where she underwent CCTA. (A) Curved multiplanar reformatted image shows propagation of IMH (black arrowhead), proximal to the LAD stent and extending to the first diagonal branch (white arrowhead). (B, C) Images show IMH in the LAD (black arrowhead in B), left circumflex coronary artery (LCX) (white arrowhead in B), and RCA (arrowheads in C) with associated fat stranding. At admission, the patient was managed with medication and underwent follow-up CCTA 3 months later. (D, E) Follow-up CCTA images show complete resolution of IMH in the LAD (arrow in D) and LCX (arrow in E). (F) There is now an intimal dissection flap (arrow) at the site of previous RCA IMH."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210062/asset/images/large/rg.2021210062.fig16.jpeg" height="3176" width="3400" aria-labelledby="fig16" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16</span>. SCAD in a 36-year-old, 3-months-postpartum woman who was diagnosed with STEMI at an outside institution and treated with drug-eluting stents to the mid and distal LAD and first obtuse marginal branch (OM1) for subtotal LAD occlusion, possible SCAD, and probable thrombotic OM1 occlusion. On continued chest pain following percutaneous coronary intervention, she was transferred to our institution where she underwent CCTA. <b>(A)</b> Curved multiplanar reformatted image shows propagation of IMH (black arrowhead), proximal to the LAD stent and extending to the first diagonal branch (white arrowhead). <b>(B, C)</b> Images show IMH in the LAD (black arrowhead in <b>B</b>), left circumflex coronary artery (LCX) (white arrowhead in <b>B</b>), and RCA (arrowheads in <b>C</b>) with associated fat stranding. At admission, the patient was managed with medication and underwent follow-up CCTA 3 months later. <b>(D, E)</b> Follow-up CCTA images show complete resolution of IMH in the LAD (arrow in <b>D</b>) and LCX (arrow in <b>E</b>). <b>(F)</b> There is now an intimal dissection flap (arrow) at the site of previous RCA IMH.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210062&amp;id=fig16">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Hayes SN, Tweet MS, Adlam D, et al. Spontaneous coronary artery dissection: JACC state-of-the-art review. <em>J Am Coll Cardiol</em> 2020;76(8):961–984.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jacc.2020.05.084">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32819471/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Spontaneous+coronary+artery+dissection%3A+JACC+state-of-the-art+review&amp;author=SN+Hayes&amp;author=MS+Tweet&amp;author=D+Adlam&amp;publication_year=2020&amp;journal=J+Am+Coll+Cardiol&amp;pages=961-984&amp;doi=10.1016%2Fj.jacc.2020.05.084&amp;pmid=32819471">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">2.</div><div id="r2" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Kim ESH. Spontaneous coronary-artery dissection. <em>N Engl J Med</em> 2020;383(24):2358–2370.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1056/NEJMra2001524">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33296561/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-